[[Image:Sanch perpignan 2007 (18).jpg|290px|thumb|right|The famous "Sanch Procession" folklore, once forbidden by the [[Catholic Church]], is still celebrated in [[Perpignan]], [[Arles-sur-Tech]] and [[Collioure]].]] The '''Procession de la Sanch''' ('''Processó de la Sanch''' in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]) is an annual ceremony in several towns in the [[Northern Catalonia|French Catalonia]]. It is held during [[Holy Week]] on [[Good Friday]] ('Vendredi Saint'/'Divendres Sant'). Historically, a distinctive peaked, masked robe (the [[Capirote|capirote]]) was used to protect the identity of prisoners (from revenge by those wronged) being led to their town's annual execution. This practical ceremony intermingled with Christian traditions of Good Friday, and today a long procession of black-robed people are led in silence by the red-robed ''regidor'' to the solemn tapping of a tambourine, as part of the Good Friday celebrations.<ref>[http://www.anglophone-direct.com/La-procession-de-la-Sanch Description of the ceremony]</ref>
